        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Tuesday 31</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write merely to thank you for your note with the desired information.— As soon as I can find out how many Cordillera shells require illustration, I will immediately decide upon the number of the Tertiary &amp; make arrangements for you to commence.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Yours faithfully | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter has a mourning border, presumably for Elizabeth (Bessy) Wedgwood, Emma’s mother, who died on 31 March 1846.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In the appendix of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1680.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Forbes</ref> described eleven species of Secondary shells of the Cordillera and George Brettingham Sowerby described sixty species of the Tertiary formations of South America. Both sets are illustrated by G. B. Sowerby Jr.</note>
        </div>        
            
